An Elastic IP (EIP) in AWS VPC is a static, public IPv4 address that you can allocate to your account and associate with EC2 instances or network interfaces, ensuring a consistent public endpoint even if the underlying instance changes. It’s especially useful for failover, DNS stability, and internet-facing applications.

🔑 Key Concepts of Elastic IP in VPC
Static Public IPv4 Address

Unlike automatically assigned public IPs, Elastic IPs remain fixed until you release them.

They provide a permanent endpoint for applications and services.

Association Options

Can be associated with instances or network interfaces.

Associating with a network interface allows you to move the interface (and its IP) between instances in one step.

Failover Capability

If an instance fails, you can remap the EIP to another instance in the same VPC.

This minimizes downtime and ensures service continuity.

Internet Access Requirement

To use an EIP for inbound/outbound traffic, your VPC must have an Internet Gateway attached.

Security Groups and NACLs must allow traffic.

⚙️ How to Use Elastic IPs
Allocate an Elastic IP

Go to VPC Console → Elastic IPs → Allocate Elastic IP.

Choose a network border group (availability zone/local zone grouping).

Associate with Resource

Attach the EIP to an EC2 instance or ENI.

If associated with the primary ENI, the existing public IP is released.

Disassociate/Remap

You can disassociate and reassign the EIP to another resource as needed.

Release

If no longer required, release the EIP back to AWS’s pool.


📊 Comparison: Elastic IP vs Public IP
Feature	                 Elastic IP (EIP)	                Auto-assigned Public IP
Persistence	          Static until released	                 Changes on stop/start
Failover Support	  Yes, can remap to another instance	    No
Cost	              Free when in use; 
                      charged if allocated but unused	      Free
Association             	Instance or ENI	                  Instance only
Use Case	        DNS stability, production apps, 
                              failover	                      Temporary internet access

⚠️ Limitations & Considerations
Quota: Default limit is 5 Elastic IPs per account per region. Use NAT gateways if more are needed.

IPv6: Elastic IPs are not supported for IPv6.

Cost: AWS charges for unused EIPs (allocated but not associated).

Security: Always configure Security Groups and NACLs properly to avoid exposure.

✅ Bottom Line: Elastic IPs in AWS VPC provide a reliable, static public IP for internet-facing workloads, ensuring high availability and DNS stability. For interviews or practical use, focus on allocation, association with ENIs, failover benefits, and cost considerations.